  "runtimeMin": 129,
  "format": "Anemone brings Daniel Day-Lewis out of retirement, so Sean, Amanda, and Blank Check's David Sims take stock of the fall slate, then grade every film he's made and vote ten of them into a Hall of Fame.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Flop fall and the 2025 slate",
      "note": "state of the year",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "One Battle After Another",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The totem of the year and the exception to 'flop fall'; David's No. 2 of 2025."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sinners",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The one big movie that stuck with all three; likely to matter in a season short on catching fall titles."
        },
        {
          "title": "Weapons",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Part of the quartet of bigger movies David couldn't stop thinking about."
        },
        {
          "title": "28 Years Later",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "David's pick for the underrated one of the four."
        },
        {
          "title": "Jay Kelly",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Baumbach's Clooney film; stuff to like, not his best, and, per David, sent to Venice when it wanted Toronto."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Smashing Machine",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Another noble swing that doesn't quite grasp everything it reaches for."
        },
        {
          "title": "Highest 2 Lowest",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Grouped with Jay Kelly and Smashing Machine as interesting efforts short of their makers' best."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sentimental Value",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "One of the Cannes titles Amanda rates above the fall festival crop."
        },
        {
          "title": "It Was Just an Accident",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Panahi's Cannes winner, cited alongside Sentimental Value as the best of the year's festivals."
        },
        {
          "title": "No Other Choice",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Park Chan-wook; Amanda loved it and expects it near the top of her list."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Testament of Ann Lee",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Amanda's near-lock for high on her list; David watched older Italian audiences walk out."
        },
        {
          "title": "Eddington",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "A movie David liked; he argues it belonged at Venice, not Cannes."
        },
        {
          "title": "Jurassic World Rebirth",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "David is angry about it; Alex Ross Perry's defense that it's everything good about the movies gets a laugh, not a co-sign."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wicked: For Good",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "One of the big titles that could reshape a bigger-movie awards race."
        },
        {
          "title": "Avatar: Fire and Ash",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Slight worry it lands smaller than Way of Water; fatigue, not quality."
        },
        {
          "title": "Avatar: The Way of Water",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "The re-release that met a shrug this time; the 'does anyone care about Avatar' bit again."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hamnet",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Named as fall prestige David still hadn't seen."
        },
        {
          "title": "Marty Supreme",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Another fall title left unseen at recording."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Anemone’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Anemone",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The film that ended Day-Lewis's eight-year retirement, directed by his son Ronan and co-written by Day-Lewis, his first writing credit. Beautiful (Northern England, great moss) but unsuccessful: abstract until it stops and explains itself, and a first-time filmmaker's movie. The 20-minute poop monologue is the most arresting thing in it. Everyone agrees it does not go in."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Every Daniel Day-Lewis movie",
      "note": "green = in, yellow = maybe, red = out",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Sunday Bloody Sunday",
          "year": 1971,
          "note": "A walk-on in John Schlesinger's film; his first screen appearance, years before he trained. Out."
        },
        {
          "title": "Gandhi",
          "year": 1982,
          "note": "One scene as Colin, a racist thug who insults Gandhi. Memorable two minutes, too small to count. Out."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Bounty",
          "year": 1984,
          "note": "The third Mutiny on the Bounty remake, with Hopkins and Gibson; he's John Fryer, fine in support. Out."
        },
        {
          "title": "My Beautiful Laundrette",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "Stephen Frears; the breakthrough. Charming and punky, near-supporting but the one that made him. In."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Room with a View",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "Merchant Ivory; he's the priggish Cecil, comes in 45 minutes deep. A great movie, but not his. Yellow, then cut."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nanou",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "An obscure French-set romantic drama with Imogen Stubbs; a barely-there part that vanished from his history. Out."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Unbearable Lightness of Being",
          "year": 1988,
          "note": "Philip Kaufman's Kundera adaptation; his first real lead and his one turn as a pure heartthrob. In, on the strength of holding a 2h45 epic."
        },
        {
          "title": "Stars and Bars",
          "year": 1988,
          "note": "Pat O'Connor fish-out-of-water comedy with a stacked cast; the rare film where he's genuinely bad. Out."
        },
        {
          "title": "My Left Foot",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "Jim Sheridan; Christy Brown and his first Oscar. The showy, natural transformation that became shorthand for the whole method mystique. In."
        },
        {
          "title": "Eversmile, New Jersey",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "Carlos Sorin; an Irish-American dentist evangelizing tooth care across Patagonia. Bad and charming, mostly forgotten. Out."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Last of the Mohicans",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "Michael Mann; peak marquee-idol Day-Lewis and a credible action star. Made $150M and announced him. Auto-green."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Age of Innocence",
          "year": 1993,
          "note": "First Scorsese; a movie whose reputation arrived late. Restraint and repression; the one film where the hosts admit another actor might have worked. In."
        },
        {
          "title": "In the Name of the Father",
          "year": 1993,
          "note": "Second Sheridan; Gerry Conlon and the Guildford Four. A great, sober Troubles film and a rare regular-guy role, undervalued now. In."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Crucible",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "Nicholas Hytner; John Proctor, adapted by Arthur Miller, whose daughter Rebecca he met on set. All righteous intensity, no person underneath. 'Straight to homework.' Out."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Boxer",
          "year": 1997,
          "note": "Third and final Sheridan; an ex-IRA man going straight. He learned to box; the film is fine, lesser than In the Name of the Father, and the repeat card that got cut."
        },
        {
          "title": "Gangs of New York",
          "year": 2002,
          "note": "Scorsese again after a five-year retirement; Bill the Butcher, the over-enunciated voice everyone imitated, and a should-have-been-third Oscar that went to Adrien Brody. In."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Ballad of Jack and Rose",
          "year": 2005,
          "note": "Directed by his wife Rebecca Miller; an off-the-grid father, an Irish Mosquito Coast. Divisive and largely forgotten. Out."
        },
        {
          "title": "There Will Be Blood",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "PTA; Daniel Plainview, the calling card, a true spiral. A front-runner for best performance of the century. In."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nine",
          "year": 2009,
          "note": "Rob Marshall's musical of 8½; he's Guido Contini, a late replacement for Javier Bardem. His singing isn't the problem. Marshall is. Out."
        },
        {
          "title": "Lincoln",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "Spielberg; the reverse-culty banger, funnier than it's remembered. Also his first acting Oscar out of a Spielberg film. In."
        },
        {
          "title": "Phantom Thread",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "PTA; Reynolds Woodcock. The film that finally let him be funny by playing the uptight British version of himself, and supposedly the one that broke him. In."
        }
      ]
    },
